' =====================================================================
' The single note kept inline — Buffer vs Window split is a visual
' reference users want to scan; everything else lives in ARCHITECTURE.md.
' =====================================================================
note as N3b #EEFFEE
  **Buffer vs Window — what goes where.**
  Rule of thumb: anything that would *differ* if the
  same content were shown in two viewports goes on
  Window; anything shared goes on Buffer.

  | concern         | Buffer | Window |
  |-----------------|--------|--------|
  | lines / text    |   X    |        |
  | extmarks        |   X    |        |
  |  (highlights,   |        |        |
  |   signs, virt   |        |        |
  |   text)         |        |        |
  | modifiable flag |   X    |        |
  | undo history    |   X    |        |
  | on_change cb    |   X    |        |
  | cursor pos      |        |   X    |
  | scroll offset   |        |   X    |
  | selection range |        |   X    |
  | keymap overlay  |        |   X    |
  | scrollbar state |        |   X    |
  | border / title  |  —     |   —    |  ' on LayoutTree (any container)
  | panel dividers  |  —     |   —    |  ' on LayoutTree (parent)

  Same Buffer can have 0..N Windows looking at it
  with independent cursors/scrolls. No BufferView
  middle layer.

  **Composing widgets**: a "dialog with a list +
  text input" is **N Windows in one Overlay**. The
  Overlay's `layout` is a Vbox/Hbox of `Leaf(WinId)`s,
  with chrome on the Vbox/Hbox itself.
  No compound-widget type, no group type — every
  composite shape is N×Window inside an Overlay.

  **Rendering model**: event-driven + diff-based,
  no dirty flag. The loop renders after every
  event; the compositor diffs current vs previous
  Grid and flushes only changed cells. Idle CPU
  is zero (loop parks). Things that change over
  time (clock, spinner) drive a `Cell` from a
  timer; the Cell setter wakes the loop.
end note

